 Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":42,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert Wilford was born about 1340, in Exeter, Devon, England, his father, William Wilford, was 32 and his mother, Mrs William Wilford, was 27. He had at least 2 sons with Elizabeth. He died before 28 August 1396, in his hometown."},"et":{"about 1340–before 28 August 1396":"umbes 1340–enne 28. augustit 1396","1340–1396":"1340–1396","1345–1378":"1345–1378","1366–1413":"1366–1413","1368–1418":"1368–1418","1310–Male":"1310–Surnud","1315–Female":"1315–Surnud","before 28 August 1396":"enne 28. augustit 1396","1396":"1396","1340":"1340","1382":"1382","1315":"1315","1413":"1413","1368":"1368","1378":"1378","1345":"1345","1366":"1366","1310":"1310","about 1368":"umbes 1368","about 1366":"umbes 1366","1418":"1418","about 1340":"umbes 1340","after 1378":"pärast 1378","Exeter, Devon, England":"Exeter, Devon, England"},"fi":{"about 1340–before 28 August 1396":"noin 1340–ennen vuotta 28. elokuuta